Well written article. But I would say it is a deliberate omission on your part that you have chosen not to talk about the other side of the coin too, not that you do not know about it. I have read articles written by people from armed forces about this. Here goes, while one rank, one pension has a credible arguement in that a brigadier retired 20 years ago, gets a lower pension than a captain recently retired, no doubt, but it also prevents a recently promoted brigadier from receiving the same or more pension than a much senior brigadier. Not just a brigadier, but any rank in the army. Simply because pay scales do get better each year for new candidates and this means an army man needs to spend fewer years to reach a specific pension than earlier. One pension, One rank will only deepen this divide further. The army has to worry about the morale of the soldiers who are serving currently, than those who are not in active service. We cannot have the apple and eat it too.
