Author::::<a href="http://social.ndtv.com/groups.php?id=647553" target="_blank">G R Srinivasan</a>

Comment::::<div class="com_user_text">
                            This is a blithely made argument that ignores economic progression and reality. While the concept does sound good on paper and in politics and is a gut wrenching issue, what is not being considered is economic reality. Inflation and PPP have most certainly continued to take their toll on pensions not commensurately indexed appropriately and hence this issue. However, how does one factor in the benefits that accrued to  those ahead in time who acquired assets like real estate, gold etc at old rates and which are infinitely more valuable now ?<br/>
The Indian middle class invests in these two asset classes as a hedge against inflation and obviously, those who came first have the 'first mover' advantage.<br/>
Therefore, just a demand of equalization at current parity is a reward which cannot be , in totality , deserving.<br/>
The moral of the story for those of today is that inflation is a silent killer of one's dignity after retirement and it is essential to invest in inflation proof assets. Of course, Indian ethos also means that children will continue to support parents and this , hopefully, continues to be inculcated.
